8 Noviodunum] two other places of this name are mentioned iu the B. G, cf. vu. 12, 55. Itis generally supposed that our Noviodunum occupied the site of the town of Soissons though Desjardins hesitates to affirm this: M. Peigne-Delacourt places it at Noyon where there are clear traces of a Gaulish oppidum, but the distance ol this place from Berry·au·Bac, between 40 and 50 Roman miles, adds greatly to the difficulties of the narrative; besides as Desjardins says, Caesar would in that case have mentioned the passage of the Oise. The Suessiones had ra oppido and it is probable that more than one of these may have been named Noviodunum which appears to be equivalent to the name now so common iu this part of France ‘Neul·cbateau’; cf. such widespread names as Neapolis, Newtown‚ Newton, Neuville, Neustadt‚ etc.
